Project Idea and Motivation

Airlines operate in an industry where fuel costs heavily influence financial performance. Fuel is one of their largest and most unpredictable expenses, so movements in crude oil prices immediately affect profitability. When crude oil prices increase, operating costs rise and airline margins shrink. When prices decrease, airlines benefit from lower expenses and stronger earnings. Since jet fuel is refined directly from crude oil, changes in major benchmarks such as West Texas Intermediate and Brent often pass quickly into jet fuel prices. These shifts can then influence how airline stocks behave in the short term.

This project examines how fluctuations in crude oil and jet fuel prices relate to stock movements in major United States airlines including Delta, American, United, and Southwest. These companies are widely traded and highly sensitive to changes in fuel conditions, which makes them ideal for studying the connection between energy markets and financial markets. For investors and analysts, knowing how strongly airline stocks react to oil price changes provides useful insight for forecasting and risk assessment. For airline managers, it highlights the importance of strategies such as hedging, long term fuel planning, and investments in efficient aircraft. More broadly, the project shows how global events that influence crude oil prices can affect industries outside the energy sector, illustrating how data driven analysis can help explain these relationships. In summary:

Problem - Why oil price volatility matters for airlines?

  • Fuel is one of the largest and most unpredictable operating expenses for airline companies.
  • Changes in crude oil or jet fuel prices directly influence planning, budgeting, and daily operating decisions.
  • Incorrect fuel cost projections can weaken airline stock performance and reduce investor confidence.

Motivation - What benefits does this analysis provide?

  • Understanding these relationships will helps airlines and investors stay profitable.
  • It supports better planning and strategic decision-making for airline companies.
  • It also helps companies to have better risk management strategies.

Key Domain Terms

Fuel Exposure
The degree to which changes in fuel prices influence an airlines operating costs, profitability, and stock performance.

WTI Crude Oil Price
West Texas Intermediate is a major benchmark for crude oil. It reflects conditions in the United States energy market and is widely used as a reference price for global oil trading.

Jet Fuel Price
The refined petroleum product used by airlines. Jet fuel prices represent a direct measure of fuel cost for airline operators and often react more sharply to market disruptions than crude oil.

Airline Stock Returns
The daily percentage change in the stock price of an airline. In this project we use log returns, which measure the natural logarithm of the price ratio from one day to the next. Log returns make different assets comparable and simplify statistical analysis.

Airline Tickers
DAL represents Delta Air Lines.
AAL represents American Airlines.
UAL represents United Airlines.
LUV represents Southwest Airlines.
These tickers are used to identify each airline in the market data.

Daily Log Return
A transformation of daily price changes that takes the natural logarithm of the ratio of consecutive prices. This measure removes long term trends, stabilizes the scale, and helps compare assets with different price levels.

Normalized Price Series
A transformation that sets the first value of a price series to one and scales all other values relative to that starting point. Normalization is used to compare growth patterns of different assets on the same chart.

Volatility
A measure of how much returns fluctuate over time. In this project we compute rolling volatility using the standard deviation of daily log returns. Higher volatility means greater uncertainty and larger price movements.

Correlation
A statistic that measures how closely two financial series move together. Positive values indicate the series move in the same direction. Negative values indicate they move in opposite directions. Values near zero indicate little connection.

Rolling Correlation
A dynamic correlation computed over a moving time window. It shows how relationships between variables such as jet fuel and airline stocks change over time.

Cross Correlation with Lags
A method that measures how one series responds to changes in another with delays. Negative lags show how airline stocks react after fuel prices move. Positive lags show whether airline prices move before fuel markets.

Regression Model
A statistical tool that estimates how much changes in WTI and jet fuel explain changes in airline stock returns. In this project we use simple ordinary least squares models to compare sensitivity across airlines.

Research Questions

  1. How do changes in crude oil prices influence jet fuel prices, and how do these fuel cost dynamics affect airline stock performance?

    This question focuses on the relationship between global energy markets and airline financial outcomes. Because jet fuel is refined from crude oil, movements in oil prices often translate into changes in jet fuel costs, which are a major component of airline operating expenses. By examining how fluctuations in oil prices feed into jet fuel prices and, in turn, into airline stock performance, this analysis highlights how energy cost volatility shapes profitability, investor expectations, and short-term market behavior in the airline industry.

  2. Which airlines appear more resilient to rising fuel costs, and what factors might explain these differences?

    This question investigates which airlines are better positioned to manage increases in fuel costs and the factors that contribute to that resilience. The analysis highlights how operational efficiency, fuel hedging, and business strategy shape each airlines ability to navigate periods of energy price volatility.

  3. Between crude oil and jet fuel prices, which serves as a stronger indicator of airline performance, and how can this insight support financial forecasting or risk management?

    This question evaluates whether crude oil or jet fuel prices provide a stronger explanation for changes in airline performance. The results can help both managers and investors focus on the most relevant energy indicators when developing forecasts or planning risk mitigation strategies.

ETL and Analysis Plan

For this notebook, we created a complete ETL pipeline to prepare the data for time series analysis and modeling. Our goal was to build a clean and consistent dataset that supports correlation analysis, rolling volatility measures, beta estimation, lagged relationships, and event based evaluation.

  1. Extract WTI crude oil prices and Jet Fuel spot prices from FRED using pandas datareader.

  2. Extract daily stock prices for Delta, American, United, and Southwest from Yahoo Finance using yfinance.

  3. Align all series on a unified daily date index and handle missing dates through forward filling so that every variable has a complete time series.

  4. Merge the WTI, Jet Fuel, and airline stock data into a single tidy DataFrame for analysis.

  5. Compute daily log returns for all variables in order to place them on a comparable scale and remove long term trends.

  6. Prepare the cleaned returns dataset for statistical work, including correlation analysis, rolling volatility calculations, lagged return relationships, and regression modeling.

  7. Estimate rolling beta values to measure how sensitive each airline stock is to movements in crude oil returns over different window lengths.

  8. Conduct event based analysis to examine how airline stocks react to major economic and geopolitical periods such as market shocks, political events, and energy price disruptions.

This ETL process created a reliable and structured dataset that supports every analytical step in the project. It confirms that we can extract real world financial and energy data, clean it into a unified format, apply transformations such as log returns, and prepare the data for meaningful statistical and visual analysis in Python.

Assumptions and Data Challenges

During the ETL and cleaning stages, we began to notice several practical challenges in the raw data. These issues also appeared during the early steps of visualization and modeling. These challenges emerged as we aligned different data sources, examined missing values, observed price behavior over time, and tested how well the variables performed in statistical models. The points below summarize the specific issues we encountered and explain the reasoning behind how we addressed them.

Calendar mismatch: Oil prices are reported every day including weekends and holidays, while stock markets close on non trading days. This mismatch became visible when merging the datasets, so forward filling was used to align all series on a unified calendar.

Negative oil prices: In April 2020, WTI briefly turned negative. This extreme but historically important event appeared during initial visual inspection. It was kept in the dataset but interpreted carefully so that modeling results were not distorted.

Non stationarity: Both crude oil prices and stock prices show long term drift rather than stable averages. This became clear through plots and summary statistics. For meaningful modeling, we use daily returns instead of raw prices.

Data accuracy and consistency: All data was obtained from reputable sources such as FRED, EIA, and Yahoo Finance. While these sources are considered reliable, missing values and slight timing differences required careful cleaning to maintain consistency.

Stable macroeconomic environment: The analysis focuses on the five year period from 2019 to 2024. Broader forces such as the pandemic, interest rate policy, and geopolitical events were not modeled directly, though they may influence the results indirectly.

Simplified study scope: This study examines short term market relationships between crude oil, jet fuel, and airline stock prices. Broader economic factors such as demand shifts, currency movements, or policy changes are beyond the scope of this analysis.

What does Adjusted Close mean?
Adjusted Close is the stock price that has been corrected for dividends, stock splits, and other corporate actions. These adjustments ensure that historical prices remain consistent over time, especially when calculating returns.

Why we use Adjusted Close:
Because it reflects the true economic value of holding the stock on each day, Adjusted Close is the standard and correct choice for computing returns in financial analysis.

We use the yfinance library and select the Adj Close column to ensure our return calculations are accurate and comparable over time.

Section 2. Aligning and Merging Price Data

In this section, we put all series on a single consistent daily timeline and combine them into one DataFrame. First, we create a master daily date index that runs from the earliest date in any series to the latest date. Then we reindex the WTI, jet fuel, and airline stock data to this index and forward-fill missing values, so each day has a defined price equal to the most recent available observation. Finally, we merge the three datasets into a single DataFrame called `prices`, where each row corresponds to a date and each column corresponds to a price series. This aligned price dataset will be the basis for computing returns and running the exploratory analysis.

In[9]:
# Section 2  Aligning and Merging Price Data

# ---- Creating a unified daily date index across all datasets ----
# Finding the earliest and latest dates across WTI, Jet Fuel, and airline stock data
# to define a single continuous timeline shared by all series.
min_date = min(wti.index.min(), jet.index.min(), stocks.index.min())
max_date = max(wti.index.max(), jet.index.max(), stocks.index.max())

# Building a complete daily date range that spans the entire period.
full_index = pd.date_range(start=min_date, end=max_date, freq="D")
print("Unified index from", full_index.min().date(), "to", full_index.max().date())
print("Number of days in unified index:", len(full_index))

# ---- Reindexing each dataset onto the unified timeline ----
# Reindexing and forward-filling missing dates (weekends/holidays) so that
# every series has a value for every day in the timeline.
wti_full = wti.reindex(full_index).ffill()
jet_full = jet.reindex(full_index).ffill()
stocks_full = stocks.reindex(full_index).ffill()

print("\nShapes after reindexing and forward-fill:")
print("WTI:", wti_full.shape)
print("JetFuel:", jet_full.shape)
print("Stocks:", stocks_full.shape)

# ---- Merging all aligned series into a single DataFrame ----
# Combining WTI, Jet Fuel, and airline stock prices column-wise to create
# one unified price table.
prices = pd.concat([wti_full, jet_full, stocks_full], axis=1)

# Renaming the index and arranging columns in a consistent order for readability.
prices.index.name = "Date"
prices = prices[["WTI", "JetFuel"] + tickers]

print("\nMerged prices shape:", prices.shape)
print("\nMissing values per column:")
print(prices.isna().sum())

print("\nHead of merged prices:")
print(prices.head())

Section 3. Computing Daily Log Returns

In this section, we convert all price series into daily log returns. Price levels cannot be compared directly across oil, jet fuel, and airline stocks because each series operates on a different scale and follows long-term trends. Log returns solve this by measuring the relative day-to-day percentage change in each series.

To compute log returns, we take the natural logarithm of each price series and calculate the first difference. The daily log return formula is:

$$ r_{t} = \ln(P_{t}) - \ln(P_{t-1}) = \ln\left(\frac{P_{t}}{P_{t-1}}\right) $$

This transformation standardizes all variables, removes long-term trends, and produces a clean returns DataFrame used for all subsequent analysis and visualization.

For more info, check: https://quant.stackexchange.com/questions/70997/how-to-calculate-the-log-return-of-portfolio

In[10]:
# Section 3  Computing Daily Log Returns

# Take natural log of prices
log_prices = np.log(prices)

# Compute daily log returns
returns = log_prices.diff().dropna()

# Print basic info
print("Returns shape:", returns.shape)
print("\nHead of returns:")
print(returns.head())

Section 4.1. Normalized Price Trend: WTI vs Jet Fuel

In this step, we compare how crude oil prices and jet fuel prices moved over time by normalizing both series to a common starting point. Normalization sets the first value of each series to 1 and scales the remaining values accordingly. This allows us to compare their relative growth or decline on the same chart, even though the two series have very different price levels.

The normalization formula is:

$$ \text{Normalized Value}_t = \frac{P_t}{P_0} $$

where:

  • (P_t) is the price on day (t)
  • (P_0) is the first available price in the sample

With this transformation, both WTI and jet fuel begin at 1 on the first day. Any movement afterward reflects relative percentage-like growth. This makes it easy to see whether jet fuel closely follows crude oil or diverges during specific periods.

For more info, check: https://www.tradingview.com/script/FGfm4xxj-Normalized-Price-Comparison/

In[11]:
# Section 4.1  Normalized Price Trend: WTI vs Jet Fuel

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Normalize both series to start at 1
normalized = prices[["WTI", "JetFuel"]] / prices[["WTI", "JetFuel"]].iloc[0]

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.plot(normalized.index, normalized["WTI"], label="WTI (normalized)")
plt.plot(normalized.index, normalized["JetFuel"], label="Jet Fuel (normalized)")
plt.title("Normalized Price Trend: WTI vs Jet Fuel")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Normalized Value")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The normalized price trend shows how WTI crude oil and jet fuel prices evolved relative to their starting values over the sample period. Both series generally move together, reflecting the strong cost link between crude oil and refined jet fuel. However, jet fuel displays noticeably larger swings, especially during 2022. It indicates higher sensitivity to refinery capacity, transportation constraints, and demand. After mid-2022, both commodities decline, but jet fuel continues to show sharper fluctuations, highlighting its greater volatility. Overall, the graph illustrates that while jet fuel follows the direction of WTI, it reacts more intensely to market changes, making it more volatile than crude oil.

# Section 4.5  Rolling 30-Day Correlations: Jet Fuel vs Airlines

window = 30
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))

for t in tickers:
    rolling_corr = returns["JetFuel"].rolling(window).corr(returns[t])
    plt.plot(rolling_corr.index, rolling_corr, label=f"JetFuel vs {t}")

plt.title("Rolling 30-Day Correlation: Jet Fuel vs Airline Returns")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Correlation")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

This rolling correlation chart shows how the relationship between jet fuel returns and each airline stock changes over time. The correlations move up and down frequently, which means the link between fuel prices and airline returns is not stable but shifts with market conditions. At some points the correlations rise above zero, showing periods when airline stocks move in the same direction as jet fuel. At other times the correlations fall toward zero or become negative, showing weaker or even opposite movements. These fluctuations suggest that fuel costs do not have a constant daily effect on airline performance and that other factors such as demand, earnings news, and broad market conditions often dominate. Overall, the rolling correlations indicate that the influence of jet fuel on airline returns is variable and depends on the economic environment rather than following a fixed pattern.

Section 4.8. Lagged Cross-Correlation: Fuel vs Airline Stocks

In this step, we compute lagged cross-correlations between jet fuel returns and airline stock returns. The purpose is to test whether movements in fuel prices lead or lag airline market reactions. We calculate correlations at multiple lags (e.g., 10 to +10 days). A positive lag indicates that jet fuel moves first and airline stocks react later; a negative lag indicates the opposite. This analysis helps identify short-term predictive relationships useful for forecasting and risk management.

In[18]:
# Section 4.8  Lagged Cross-Correlation

import numpy as np

# Define lag range (e.g., -10 to +10 days)
lags = range(-10, 11)

def cross_corr(series1, series2, lag):
    """Computes correlation with the specified lag."""
    if lag > 0:
        return series1.shift(lag).corr(series2)
    elif lag < 0:
        return series1.corr(series2.shift(-lag))
    else:
        return series1.corr(series2)

results = {}

for ticker in ['DAL', 'AAL', 'UAL', 'LUV']:
    results[ticker] = [cross_corr(returns['JetFuel'], returns[ticker], lag) for lag in lags]

# Plot results
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for ticker in results:
    plt.plot(lags, results[ticker], label=f'JetFuel vs {ticker}')

plt.axhline(0, color='black', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('Lag (days)')
plt.ylabel('Cross-Correlation')
plt.title('Lagged Cross-Correlation: Jet Fuel vs Airline Stock Returns')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The lagged cross correlation plot shows how jet fuel returns and airline stock returns move relative to each other when one series is shifted forward or backward in time. The values remain small at all lags, which means the relationship between fuel price changes and airline stock movements is weak. The highest correlations appear when lags are negative, around ten to three days, indicating that airline returns usually respond a few days after changes in jet fuel prices. Positive lags are smaller, suggesting that airline stocks almost never move ahead of fuel prices. Overall, the pattern shows that fuel price movements lead airline stock movements, but the effect is limited in size, meaning that jet fuel shocks influence airline stocks only slightly and with a short delay.

5.1. Regression Setup 1: Modeling How Oil and Jet Fuel Affect Airline Stock Returns

In this section, we estimate how changes in WTI crude oil prices and jet fuel prices affect airline stock returns. We use a simple linear regression model where daily airline stock returns are explained by daily returns of WTI and Jet Fuel. This helps us quantify whether fuel markets have a measurable impact on airline performance, and which fuel variable is more influential. We estimate separate models for each airline to compare sensitivity across carriers.

In[19]:
import statsmodels.api as sm

# Prepare regression dataset
reg_data = returns[['WTI', 'JetFuel', 'DAL', 'AAL', 'UAL', 'LUV']].dropna()

# Function to run regression for each airline
def run_regression(y_col):
    X = reg_data[['WTI', 'JetFuel']]
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    y = reg_data[y_col]
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    return model

5.2 Regression Setup 2: Modeling How Oil and Jet Fuel Affect Airline Stock Returns

Rolling window regression is used to examine how the relationship between fuel prices and airline stock returns changes over time. Instead of fitting one single regression to the entire dataset, the model is repeatedly estimated on a short moving window, such as sixty days. This approach recognizes that financial relationships are not constant and may shift due to changes in demand conditions, market events, or economic cycles. Rolling regression allows us to see whether the sensitivity of airline returns to WTI and jet fuel becomes stronger, weaker, or changes sign during specific periods. This model does not focus on predicting future values but instead evaluates the stability and time variation of the relationship, which directly supports the research goal of understanding how fuel markets influence airline performance.

In[20]:
# Rolling Window Regression

import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

window = 60  # 60 day window

rolling_betas = {ticker: {'WTI': [], 'JetFuel': [], 'Date': []} for ticker in ['DAL', 'AAL', 'UAL', 'LUV']}

for ticker in ['DAL', 'AAL', 'UAL', 'LUV']:
    for i in range(window, len(reg_data)):
        y = reg_data[ticker].iloc[i-window:i]
        X = reg_data[['WTI', 'JetFuel']].iloc[i-window:i]
        X = sm.add_constant(X)

        model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
        rolling_betas[ticker]['WTI'].append(model.params['WTI'])
        rolling_betas[ticker]['JetFuel'].append(model.params['JetFuel'])
        rolling_betas[ticker]['Date'].append(reg_data.index[i])

# Plot rolling betas for Jet Fuel
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
for ticker in ['DAL', 'AAL', 'UAL', 'LUV']:
    plt.plot(rolling_betas[ticker]['Date'], rolling_betas[ticker]['JetFuel'], label=f"{ticker} JetFuel Beta")
plt.title("Rolling Sixty Day Jet Fuel Sensitivity")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Beta Coefficient")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Plot rolling betas for WTI
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
for ticker in ['DAL', 'AAL', 'UAL', 'LUV']:
    plt.plot(rolling_betas[ticker]['Date'], rolling_betas[ticker]['WTI'], label=f"{ticker} WTI Beta")
plt.title("Rolling Sixty Day WTI Sensitivity")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Beta Coefficient")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

5.3. Event Study: Market Responses to Major Energy and Geopolitical Shocks

In this section, we conduct an event study to evaluate how major geopolitical and energy-related shocks affect short-horizon movements in crude oil prices, jet fuel prices, and U.S. airline stock returns. We use a symmetric 15-day event window around each event date. This one-month window captures the immediate market reaction as well as the short-run adjustment period that typically follows large supply shocks or geopolitical disruptions. Such events often unfold over several trading weeks, making a wider window appropriate for this context.

We compute cumulative returns for all variablesincluding WTI crude oil, jet fuel, and the airline stocks DAL, AAL, UAL, and LUVso that all series can be compared on a consistent scale. Daily returns are highly volatile and difficult to interpret during shock periods, whereas cumulative returns smooth out high-frequency noise and reveal the net directional impact over the full event window. This scaling also allows assets with different price levels to be shown together on a single figure.

By plotting cumulative returns for oil, jet fuel, and all airlines on each event, we can evaluate relative sensitivity to energy shocks. Oil and jet fuel typically react in the same direction, while airlines often respond inversely because higher fuel costs reduce profitability. The patterns in these windows help us understand the transmission of global supply disruptions into both energy markets and airline equity performance.

Event descriptions and expected short-run effects:

RussiaUkraine War (Feb 2022): A major geopolitical shock increasing perceived supply risk. Expected to raise crude and jet fuel prices and place downward pressure on airline stocks.

OPEC+ Production Cut (Oct 2022): A planned reduction in output designed to support crude prices. Usually associated with higher fuel costs and weaker airline returns.

OPEC+ Surprise Output Cut (Apr 2023): An unexpected supply cut that often produces sharper short-run adjustments in energy markets and adverse reactions in airline equities.

Middle East Conflict Escalation (Oct 2023): A regional conflict raising uncertainty around production and transport routes. Typically increases volatility in energy markets and pressures airline performance.

In[23]:
# Section 6  Event Study: Do Major Real-World Shocks Affect Airline Returns?

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Define airline tickers used in the analysis
tickers = ["DAL", "AAL", "UAL", "LUV"]

# Events chosen to capture major oil-related shocks within the dataset range
events = {
    "RussiaUkraine War Begins (Feb 2022)": "2022-02-24",
    "OPEC+ Production Cut Announcement (Oct 2022)": "2022-10-05",
    "OPEC+ Surprise Output Cut (Apr 2023)": "2023-04-02",
    "Middle East Conflict Escalation (Oct 2023)": "2023-10-07",
}

# One-month event window: 15 days before and 15 days after
window_days = 15

# Helper function to extract a symmetric event window
def get_event_window(df, event_date, window_days=15):
    event_date = pd.to_datetime(event_date)
    start = event_date - pd.Timedelta(days=window_days)
    end = event_date + pd.Timedelta(days=window_days)
    return df.loc[start:end]

# Columns to plot together (all daily log returns)
cols_to_plot = ["WTI", "JetFuel"] + tickers  # assumes these columns exist in returns

# Get available date range in your returns DataFrame
min_date = returns.index.min()
max_date = returns.index.max()

print("Your dataset covers:", min_date, "to", max_date)
print(f"Using a one-month event window of {window_days} days around each event.\n")

# Iterate through events and ONLY plot those with data
for event_name, event_date in events.items():

    event_date = pd.to_datetime(event_date)

    # Check if event is within your dataset range
    if event_date < min_date or event_date > max_date:
        print(f"Skipping '{event_name}'  event is outside dataset range.")
        continue

    # Extract window for all selected series (oil, jet fuel, and airlines)
    window_df = get_event_window(returns[cols_to_plot], event_date, window_days=window_days)

    # Skip if window is empty
    if window_df.empty:
        print(f"Skipping '{event_name}'  no data available for this window.")
        continue

    # Compute cumulative returns over the event window
    cum_df = (1 + window_df).cumprod() - 1

    # Plot cumulative returns for all series
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    for col in cols_to_plot:
        plt.plot(cum_df.index, cum_df[col],
                 linewidth=2, label=col)

    # Mark event date
    plt.axvline(event_date, linestyle="--", label="Event date")

    plt.title(f"Cumulative Returns Around Event: {event_name}")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Cumulative Return")
    plt.grid(alpha=0.3)
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Final Conclusion

This project aimed to investigate how fluctuations in oil prices, particularly WTI crude and jet fuel, affect US airline stock returns. Through multiple regression models, cumulative return analysis, and time series event studies, we evaluated both short term and lagged relationships between energy markets and airline equity performance.

We began by constructing a clean merged dataset including daily returns for WTI crude oil, jet fuel, and four major US airlines: DAL, AAL, UAL, and LUV. Exploratory data analysis revealed visible co movements between oil prices and airline stocks, especially during periods of heightened volatility in energy markets.

In our initial regressions using same day returns, we found a statistically significant negative relationship between fuel prices and airline stock returns. Rising fuel costs lower airline profits because fuel is a major operating expense. This helps explain why airline stock prices often decline when oil prices increase.

We also tested for lagged effects since markets may not react instantly to energy price changes. Using regression models with shifted return values, we observed that yesterdays oil and jet fuel returns still influenced todays airline returns, although the effect was weaker than same day relationships. This indicates some delayed pricing in by investors.

To understand how real world disruptions influence the sector, we conducted event studies using plus or minus fifteen day cumulative return windows. We examined events such as the Russia Ukraine war in February 2022, the OPEC plus production cut announcement in October 2022, the OPEC plus surprise output cut in April 2023, and the Middle East conflict escalation in October 2023.

These events revealed consistent patterns. Oil and jet fuel prices often moved sharply, and airline equities generally declined around major disruptions. Not all fuel price shocks led to airline stock losses, and other factors like investor expectations, risk management strategies, and broader economic conditions also shaped market reactions.

Across all analyses, airline stocks showed clear sensitivity to movements in oil and jet fuel prices. The relationship was not perfectly uniform across events, which suggests that airline performance depends on a mix of fuel costs, market expectations, and the nature of each disruption. These findings support the idea that the airline sector is closely tied to conditions in the global energy market.

Future Recommendations

Future work can improve this analysis by using more advanced models that can include variables such as passenger demand, capacity data, economic indicators, or airline specific operating costs. It may help explain more of the variation in stock prices. Extending the dataset over a longer time period or using intraday data could also reveal stronger patterns.These improvements can help build a more complete understanding of how energy markets influence airline performance and support better forecasting or risk management strategies.
